<div class="quotetitle">thefox wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />CC65 could also be used.<br /></div><br />In other words, the Koei route. This was done at the expense of a lot of PRG RAM.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">qbradq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I had not thought of using CC65, but I like the idea of a non-Turing complete virtual machine.<br /></div><br />No implemented programming language is Turing complete because no computer has unbounded memory. At beast, computers are linear bounded automata. Did you mean "verifiably type-safe"?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Performance is not a big concern for me. The engine itself will be implemented in assembly. Only event response will be handled by the script, and the execution can be made to extend over several frames.<br /></div><br />The player presses a button, and it takes "several frames" for Mario to jump. Mario collects a coin, and it takes "several frames" for the coin to disappear and for the player's score to get credited. Mario hits a block, and it takes "several frames" for it to hop and start to sprout a mushroom.<br /><br />Perhaps you just figured out why Micronics games run at 12 to 20 fps.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Sat Apr 30, 2011 5:40 am</p><hr />
